Targetted applications

(1): Car crash-worthiness example

10-50 thickness variables

Categorical variables (e.g., materials)

Parts can be present or not

Goal: find the best compromise between mass and safety constraints

Simulation time: minutes to hours on HPC

(2): New York Citi’s Bike System

Allocation of bikes in the city’s dock stations before rush hour.

Variables: number of bikes in 4 groups of stations

Noise: demand for bikes in the simulation period

Ref: Toscano-Palmerin, S., & Frazier, P. I. (2018). Bayesian optimization with expensive integrands. arXiv preprint arXiv:1803.08661.

(3): Hyperparameter optimization

(Convolutional) neural networks show great promises on many problems, but finding an appropriate structure can be time consuming.

These are the so-called hyperparameter tuning problems.

MNIST example:

Design variables:

  • kernel size, number of filters, number of layers
  • dropout rates

“Noise” factors:

  • dropout
  • initialization
  • data set partition

Initial ideas to tackle these problems?

How to solve \(\min_{\mathbf{x} \in D \subset \mathbf{R}^d} f(\mathbf{x})\) when \(f\) is:

  • expensive

  • black box: when no information about the functional form of \(f\) is available (e.g., not convex)

  • without derivative information (often)

  • possibly noisy



Note that we are looking for a global minimum here.

Are the optimization methods you know suitable?

Key ideas (in a nutshell)

  1. We replace \(f\) by its model \(\hat{f}\), this is called surrogate modeling or metamodeling.

  2. We go sequentially: one iteration at a time, to update \(\hat{f}\) with new data.

  3. We balance between exploration of unknown regions of the search space and exploitation of promising ones.

Definition of Bayesian optimization[1]: Sequential design strategy based on a distribution over functions to define an acquisition function.

[1] Mockus, J. (1989).Bayesian approach to global optimization. Springer.

No free lunch theorem [2]

No silver bullet: no optimizer is best on all possible classes of functions.

Examples of functions out of reach for optimization with small budgets(*):

[2] Wolpert, D.H., Macready, W.G. (1997), “No Free Lunch Theorems for Optimization”, IEEE Transactions on Evolutionary Computation 1, 67.

(*) but not for every method, see, e.g., Valko, M., Carpentier, A., & Munos, R. (2013). Stochastic simultaneous optimistic optimization. ICML (pp. 19-27).

Implementation

Many existing toolboxes in different languages.

Non-exhaustive and biased list:

  • Matlab: BayesianOptimization in the stats toolbox;

  • R: packages DiceOptim, laGP, GPareto;

  • Python: trieste, SMAC, GPyOpt, BoTorch, SpearMint
